cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.MM, cs.GT

This paper deals with wireless communication networks and scheduling schemes, which are typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The use of non-orthogonal multiple access (NOMA) technology also suggests a possible fit with the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category, as NOMA involves multiple users sharing the same channel resources. The paper also proposes a fairness-aware scheduling scheme, which involves optimizing the max-min fairness of the system, suggesting a possible fit with the Multiagent Systems (cs.MM) and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories.
